This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.

8aef128a-b54c-4c21-8382-a8861ce7d27e.1829e526-7237-48e5-ad97-8c0aca744c54.description=
This operation copies files between two remote machines using different protocols (local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB).

Inputs\:
    sourceHost - The host of the source file.
    sourcePort - The port for connecting to the source host.
    sourceUsername - The username for connecting to the host of the source file.
    sourcePassword - The password for connecting to the host of the source file.
    sourcePrivateKeyFile - Absolute path of the private key file for public/private key authentication on the source host.
    sourcePath - The absolute path to the source file. In case of FTP or SFTP protocol please use a relativ path to FTP/SFTP server root directory.
    sourceProtocol - The protocol used to copy from the source file.
Valid values\: local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB. 
    sourceCharacterSet - The name of the control encoding to use with source host for FTP and SFTP protocols. 
Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.  
Default\: for FTP, the default is ISO-8859-1 (Latin1). For SFTP, it is UTF-8.
    destinationHost - The host of the destination file.
    destinationPort - The port for connecting to the destination host.
    destinationUsername - The username for connecting to the host of the destination file.
    destinationPassword - The password for connecting to the host of the destination file.
    destinationPrivateKeyFile - Absolute path of the private key file for public/private key authentication on the destination host.
    destinationPath - The absolute path to the destination file.
    destinationProtocol - The protocol used to copy to the destination file.
Valid values\: local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB.
    destinationCharacterSet - The name of the control encoding to use with destination host for FTP and SFTP protocols. 
Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.   
Default\: for FTP, the default is ISO-8859-1 (Latin1). For SFTP, it is UTF-8.
    fileType - The type of the file being copied if using FTP. This input must be empty if FTP protocol is not used.
Valid values\: binary, ascii.
Default value\: binary
    passive - If true, passive connection mode will be enabled if using FTP.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the "Copy completed successfully" message if operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It is 0 if operation successfully completes, -1 otherwise.
    exception - It contains an exception message if something went wrong.

Responses\:
    success - The file was copied successfully.
    failure - The file could not be copied.

Examples\:
1. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Windows machine to a  Linux machine\:
        sourceHost\: server1.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username1
        sourcePasword\: password1
        sourcePath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server2.example.com
        destinationPort\: 22
        destinationUsername\: username2
        destinationPassword\: password2
        destinationPath\: /root/example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: scp
2. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Linux machine to a Windows machine\:
        sourceHost\: server2.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username2
        sourcePasword\: password2
        sourcePath\: /root/example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server1.example.com
        destinationPort\: 22
        destinationUsername\: username1
        destinationPassword\: password1
        destinationPath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: scp
3. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Linux machine to a Windows machine without prerequisites\:
        sourceHost\: server2.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username2
        sourcePasword\: password2
        sourcePath\: /root/example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server1.example.com
        destinationUsername\: username1
        destinationPassword\: password1
        destinationPath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: smb

8aef128a-b54c-4c21-8382-a8861ce7d27e.27cf4ad5-aeb7-4b42-803e-800a51ebaaa0.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.

8aef128a-b54c-4c21-8382-a8861ce7d27e.6c16e33f-d348-45f9-b911-5dfbc45d8d1c.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.

Inputs\:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE\: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns\:
The number that was just counted.

Note\: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses\:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.

8aef128a-b54c-4c21-8382-a8861ce7d27e.e33c7500-5142-4986-a6a5-7dc338a4a668.description=
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter - The string to filter on (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    iterate - Determines whether the content of the file should be iterated or not. If set to "true", the content of the file will be iterated row by row and for each subsequent call, the next row will be returned. If set to "false", the content of the file will not be iterated and only the number of lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values\: true, false
    delimiter – If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    eofReset - If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    count - The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of rows available for retrieval from the source file.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - The operation successfully read the file (if iterate is true, more rows are available).
    no more items - No more items are available for retrieval (if iterate is set to true).
    failure - The operation failed to read the file.

Notes\:
1. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
2. Note that the "filter" match is not performed based on a regular expression, although the filter field may contain one. The operation only checks for each row if it contains the string given as filter. 
3. If i"terate" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "iterate" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.
5. If the value provided in the "delimiter" field is not null, the entire file will be read once and returned regardless of the value of the "iterate" field.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the delimiter input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will be blank and the count output field will contain the value 4 (representing the number of lines in the file).
